</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=absolutemaster>Absolute Master</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 46<br> <font color=#333333>(2/11/03 6:22:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1832.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://stuwww.kub.nl/~s338419/everquest/gohan.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: let's CHARM</span><hr size=1> Enrage starts on any mob capable of it when he gets below 10% and lasts for a duration of 10 seconds. Enrage also means that NONE of your pets attacks is going through and all are getting riposted. Knowning this options to keep your pet alive or to speed up killing is to either 1) root the mob and back the pet off, 2) tank the mob so that the pet can still damage it during enrage from behind, 3) spam /pet back off (or /pet hold if you have it) and do so until enrage wears off.<br>
<br>
1 is obviously not possible with a mage solo, and 2 is doable but unless the mob is slowed or you have a rune effect on you, it is not feasible. best is to simply have it backed off. It's not gonna do any damage during that 10 seconds anyways, so best to minimize the damage it takes.<br>
<br>
BTW Also note that enrage is an ability. A caster NPC might not enrage if he is casting while below 10%. A mob which is chained stunned will not enrage either, and neither does a fleeing mob. Use that to your advantage if you can.<br>
<br>
Turonyen<br>
Level 65 Enchanter<br>
